1) Developed a new and general statistical framework to extract detailed information about the history of species and populations from genome sequence data.
2) Used this new method to make more detailed inference about the history of human populations, in particular when and where geneflow with Neandertals occurred.
3) Reconstructed the speciation process in a fruit fly model system. This research showed that species divergence can be triggered by large chromosomal rearrangements as predicted by theoretical models of speciation.
4) Ongoing and future work is comparing speciation histories across species to understand why some groups of organisms speciate more often than others.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The new inference method has wide applicability beyond the context of speciation. For example, our inferences about past, natural hybridisation between wild boar and the endangered Visayan Warty pig will inform conservation/breeding programs for this species. 

